subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
This is a very large vespertilionid, with a FA of 
78.4–83.1 mm
(
Table 1
). The dorsal pelage is dark brown and the ventral pelage is greyish-brown with an apparent whitish-brown ring on the chest between the shoulders (
Fig. 2
). The skull is massive (
Fig. 3a
) with a GTL and CCL of 29.30–31.13 and 
27.12–28.70 mm
, respectively (
Table 1
). The inner upper incisor (
I1
) is unicuspid. The upper canine (C1) is large, more than twice that of the second upper premolar (P4) (
Fig. 3a
). The first lower premolar (P2) is rounded; the second lower premolar (P4) is somewhat square (
Fig. 3a
). The anterior basal cusps of both P2 and P4 are poorly developed. The talonids of the first (M1) and second lower molars (M2) are about equal to that of their respective trigonids (
Fig. 3a
).

The skull is robust, with a GTL and CCL of 
29.30–31.13 mm
and 
27.12–28.70 mm
, respectively (
Table 1
). The inner upper incisor (
I1
) is unicuspid and relatively large, about one thirds that of the upper canine (C1) in height (
Fig. 3
). The outer incisor (
I2
), however, is very small with the height only about one third that of the 
I1.
The C1 is large, more than twice that of the second upper premolar (P4) (
Fig. 3a
). The first lower premolar (P2) is rounded; the second lower premolar (P4) is somewhat square in outline (
Fig. 3a
). The anterior basal cusps of both P2 and P4 are poorly developed. The talonids of the first (M1) and second lower molars (M2) are about equal to that of their respective trigonids (
Fig. 3a
).
